  "articleSummary": "The article argues that well-crafted multiple-choice questions (MCQs) are a powerful teaching tool, not just a testing shortcut. Its core thesis is that the wrong answers (distractors) do the real pedagogical work by exposing and correcting specific misconceptions. The author, writing in a reflective, tutorial-like tone, uses the example of a PostgreSQL syntax question to show how a single MCQ can serve learners at different expertise levels. Key points include designing distractors that mirror real misunderstandings (e.g., legacy syntax, cross-language habits) and using quiz writing to sharpen the teacher’s own precision. The intended audience is technical educators and content creators who want to build more honest, effective learning experiences.",
